  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Insufficient cognitive control over emotional distracters is characteristic for major
      depressive disorder (MDD). Hypoactivation of the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC) is
      associated with this deficit. In this study the investigators assess the effect of an
      enhancement of dlPFC activity in MDD patients by anodal transcranial direct current
      stimulation (tDCS) on cognitive control.

      In a double-blinded, balanced randomized, sham-controlled crossover trial the investigators
      determine the effect of a single-session tDCS to the left dlPFC on cognitive control in MDD
      patients and healthy controls. To assess the cognitive control the investigators use a
      delayed response working memory (DWM) task with pictures of varying valence presented during
      the delay period.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
